30 CITY OF CLAREMONT
31 SECTION 3.(a) Section 3 of the Charter of the City of Claremont, being Chapter 11
32 of the Private Laws of 1893, as amended by Chapter 76 of the 1961 Session Laws, Chapter 97 of
33 the 1975 Session Laws, S.L. 2005-54, and Town Ordinance adopted on February 3, 1976, reads
34 as rewritten:
35 "Sec. 3. Elections; Terms of mayor and councilmen.Council members.
36 (a) At the regular annual election of city officers in May, 1961, in the City of Claremont, the
37 qualified voters shall elect a mayor and five (5) councilmen.The governing body for the City of
38 Claremont shall consist of a mayor and five council members, elected to serve four-year
39 staggered terms. Regular municipal elections shall be held at the time of the general election in
40 each even-numbered year. Council members for the City of Claremont shall be elected on a
41 nonpartisan plurality basis and the results determined in accordance with G.S. 163-292. Except
42 as otherwise provided, the election shall be conducted in accordance with the uniform municipal
43 election laws in Chapter 163 of the General Statutes.
44 (b) The mayor to be elected in 2005 shall shall be elected to serve for a term of four years or
45 until a successor is duly elected and qualified. Thereafter, a mayor shall be elected every four
46 years in the odd-numbered years and the term of office shall be four years.
47 (c) Of the five (5) councilmen now holding office in the City of Claremont, Catawba County,
48 successors to the offices now held by Harold McRee Wilson, Eddy Gaither Harwell, and William
49 David Watts shall be elected at the November, 1975, election, and every four (4) years thereafter,
50 for the City of Claremont and shall serve for terms of four (4) years or until their successors are
51 elected and qualified. Successors to the offices now held by Timothy Allan Lowrance and Gary
